<SECOND>PM-Postage Examples,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Examples of Higher Postal Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Postal Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new rates proposed by the board of
governors of the U.S. Postal Service would mean higher mail costs
for most individuals and businesses.
   Here are some examples of the changes when the new rates take
effect, probably sometime in early 1991:
   _Individual cost of mailing a letter or paying a bill: 30 cents,
up from 25 cents.
   _Cost to mail a regular post card: 20 cents, up from 15 cents.
   _Price of sending a seven-pound package: $5.06, up from $4.00.
   _Charge to a bank to send a three-ounce statement: 76 cents, up
from 65 cents.
   _Department store cost to mail a pre-sorted bill: 26 cents, up
from 21 cents.
   _Price to send a credit-card bill, sorted according to the full
nine-digit ZIP code: 25.3 cents, up from 20.5 cents.
   _Utility company cost to send a bill with imprinted bar code,
allowing it to be handled by machines: 24.3 cents, up from 20 cents.
   _Lawyer's cost to send one-pound of legal documents by priority
mail: $2.75, up from $2.40.
   _Charge to send eight ounces of high-speed business information
via Express Mail: $9.75, up from $8.75.
   _Cost for two-pounds of urgent business materials via Express
Mail: $13.75, up from $12.00.
   _Postage for a typical weekly newsmagazine: 16 cents, up from
13.5 cents.
   _Cost of sending a somewhat heavier monthly magazine: 37.4
cents, up from 29.7 cents.
   _Postage for two ounces of advertising, with special bar code
imprinted to permit handling by new automated machinery: 16.1
cents, down from 16.7 cents.
   _Rate for half-pound catalog, sorted according to ZIP code: 33.1
cents, up from 27.1 cents.
   _Charge for advertising mail, sorted in advance according to the
sequence of houses that the letter carrier visits: 9.6 cents, down
from 10.1 cents.
   _Cost of sending a local three-pound business package: $2.00, up
from $1.58.
   _Book club cost to mail a four-pound package: $2,26, up from
$1.95.
</TEXT>
